article.headline: Minnesota's Big 3 combine for 75 points
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves' two All-Stars were better than the Orlando Magic's one. Kevin Garnett had 30 points and 14 rebounds, and Sam Cassell added 20 points and 10 assists to lead the Timberwolves over the Magic 113-100 Tuesday night. Latrell Sprewell added 25 points and seven assists for Minnesota, which won for the 13th time in 15 games -- and 13th straight at home. Tracy McGrady scored 34 points for Orlando, keeping the Magic in the game until midway through the fourth quarter, when Minnesota went on an 18-6 run keyed by All-Stars Garnett and Cassell. "We're going to find a way," said Cassell, who earlier in the day was selected as a reserve to his first All-Star game. "It's a heavyweight fight. You're not going to knock them out in the first round." With 9 minutes to go and Minnesota up 87-82, coach Flip Saunders reinserted Garnett into the game. Garnett then scored eight points during a 10-2 run to up the lead to 97-84. "You don't want to see him any time," Magic coach Johnny Davis said when asked about Garnett's impact in the fourth quarter. Cassell then hit a 3-pointer and later converted a three-point play to give the Wolves a 105-88 lead. The Magic, who started the season 1-19 but have played more competitively in recent weeks -- they are now 13-37, appeared to frustrate Minnesota for much of the first three quarters. McGrady scored 26 of his points over the second and third quarters, including a long 3-pointer that tied the score 69-all with 3:30 left in the third. "We don't expect any team in the league to play like their record," Garnett said. "T-Mac can definitely put up points and put them in a position to win." Fred Hoiberg, who shot just 31 percent since Jan. 1, hit consecutive 3-pointers to key Minnesota's 15-3 run to end the third. Orlando then responded with a 10-1 run early in the fourth quarter to pull within 87-82, prompting Saunders to bring Garnett back. Garnett immediately asserted himself, hitting a pair of free throws and then a long jumper. After the teams traded baskets, Garnett hit two more free throws, then made a dunk to put Minnesota up 97-84. "We know they have three big weapons," said Orlando's Juwan Howard, the only other Magic player in double figures with 17. "They can go to them at any time and cause problems for opposing defenses." The Wolves went on a 15-5 run midway through the second quarter to take a 43-37 lead, but McGrady scored nine of the Magic's final 11 points in the half to pull within 51-48 at the break. McGrady has scored 20 or more points in 17 straight games and 30 or more in eight of his last 10. In the teams' previous meeting Nov. 7 in Orlando, He had just four points on 2-of-10 shooting. Cassell reached two other milestones in addition to his All-Star selection. His 3-pointer in the third quarter was the 500th of his career, and he also extended his consecutive free throws streak to 56 by making two. "Individual honors are good," Cassell said. "But I need to thank my teammates for helping me get that honor."

Game notes
Cassell and Garnett, voted a Western Conference starter, join West head coach Saunders for the Feb. 15 All-Star game in Los Angeles. McGrady, voted an Eastern Conference starter, is Orlando's only representative. ... At 34 years and two months, Cassell is the second-oldest player to be selected to his first-ever All-Star game. Nat "Sweetwater" Clifton of the 1957 New York Knicks was a month older when he was selected. ... Orlando is 0-11 against the Midwest Division and 2-15 against the Western Conference. ... Garnett's first-quarter rebound was the 7,000th of his career.
